have a couple minutes

00:50:34.920 --> 00:50:38.000
to take a few questions, and we
might just take a few rat a tat

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:41.590
and see what Sally has to say
about them, because we have,

00:50:41.590 --> 00:50:44.090
I hope you all will stay
and enjoy the reception

00:50:44.090 --> 00:50:48.130
that the Maguire Endowment
is paying for today

00:50:48.130 --> 00:50:49.730
and that is for all of you.

00:50:49.730 --> 00:50:55.440
And so, raise your hand if
you have a question for Sally.

00:50:55.440 --> 00:50:58.990
Do not be shy.

00:50:58.990 --> 00:51:00.410
Andrew, right here.

00:51:00.410 --> 00:51:01.710
&gt;&gt; Hello.

00:51:01.710 --> 00:51:03.010
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So we'll have
these two gentlemen right here,

00:51:03.010 --> 00:51:05.400
just a quick question and
then we'll hand the microphone

00:51:05.400 --> 00:51:06.700
over to the gentleman
next to you

00:51:06.700 --> 00:51:08.530
and then we'll see
what Sally has to say.

00:51:08.530 --> 00:51:11.290
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much for
a most interesting talk.

00:51:11.290 --> 00:51:13.320
Given that you mentioned there
is some movement in the states,

00:51:13.320 --> 00:51:15.820
particularly in the
western period also,

00:51:15.820 --> 00:51:18.260
and there is interest in the
federal government in toying

00:51:18.260 --> 00:51:21.670
with Washington D.C. as they
frequently do, were there any

00:51:21.670 --> 00:51:25.620
in congress in the 1870's who
were interested in pursuing some

00:51:25.620 --> 00:51:29.430
of these exemptions
policies in the territories?

00:51:29.430 --> 00:51:30.730
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sarah Barringer
Gordon: That's a great.

00:51:30.730 --> 00:51:34.390
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
Okay, hold onto that,

00:51:34.390 --> 00:51:37.890
we're going to let this
guy ask the questions.

00:51:37.890 --> 00:51:39.190
And then, you can
handle them both.

00:51:39.190 --> 00:51:40.490
Whether they link or not.

00:51:40.490 --> 00:51:41.790
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sarah Barringer
Gordon: Yeah.

00:51:41.790 --> 00:51:43.090
&gt;&gt; So you annihilated the idea
that this was always out there.

00:51:43.090 --> 00:51:44.790
But you know, under the
idea that, you know,

00:51:44.790 --> 00:51:48.640
sometimes taxes are done to
discourage things, I'm thinking

00:51:48.640 --> 00:51:53.330
for example syntax's, I
always thought it was sort of,

00:51:53.330 --> 00:51:55.330
you know, a difficult
topic to think

00:51:55.330 --> 00:51:58.390
of taxing religious institutions
because you didn't want

00:51:58.390 --> 00:52:01.820
to discourage religion, even
though there is a separation.

00:52:01.820 --> 00:52:04.390
And then what about other
western governments,

00:52:04.390 --> 00:52:06.510
other western countries.

00:52:06.510 --> 00:52:08.180
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sarah Barringer
Gordon: Mmm-hmm.

00:52:08.180 --> 00:52:09.480
Should I answer now?

00:52:09.480 --> 00:52:10.780
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Yeah.

00:52:10.780 --> 00:52:12.960
I haven't got anybody
else indicating.

00:52:12.960 --> 00:52:14.260
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sarah Barringer
Gordon: Okay, good.

00:52:14.260 --> 00:52:15.620
So the question about
the territories is

00:52:15.620 --> 00:52:17.590
really interesting.

00:52:17.590 --> 00:52:26.600
There was, congress officially
disapproved in the late 1850's,

00:52:26.600 --> 00:52:28.810
the incorporation of the
Church of Jesus Christ

00:52:28.810 --> 00:52:31.780
of Latter Day Saints, because
it had no limits on the amount

00:52:31.780 --> 00:52:34.210
of property it could hold.

00:52:34.210 --> 00:52:39.260
So one of the things that
you can see happening,

00:52:39.260 --> 00:52:45.680
is that there was this
commitment through the onset

00:52:45.680 --> 00:52:49.930
of the Civil War, to keeping
religious property pretty

00:52:49.930 --> 00:52:51.240
tightly contained.

00:52:51.240 --> 00:52:53.090
In other words, not
allowing them

00:52:53.090 --> 00:52:55.620
to become extraordinarily
wealthy.

00:52:55.620 --> 00:52:58.950
That is gone, by 1875.

00:52:58.950 --> 00:53:01.940
So what's interesting
is to see that.

00:53:01.940 --> 00:53:05.830
In terms of other
western states,

00:53:05.830 --> 00:53:10.540
California is really interesting
because it's constitution

00:53:10.540 --> 00:53:14.570
of 1850 promised equal
taxation for everybody,

00:53:14.570 --> 00:53:18.790
which was a standard,
protect slavery clause,

00:53:18.790 --> 00:53:23.140
that was included in many
southern state constitutions.

00:53:23.140 --> 00:53:26.140
In other words, you
couldn't tax slavery higher

00:53:26.140 --> 00:53:27.440
than you taxed anything else.

00:53:27.440 --> 00:53:30.040
&gt;&gt; I was thinking about
other countries, though.

00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:33.300
Other country, European
countries.

00:53:33.300 --> 00:53:35.380
Other countries with
democracies.

00:53:35.380 --> 00:53:37.660
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sarah Barringer
Gordon: Okay.

00:53:37.660 --> 00:53:40.360
So, in the U/.K. for example,

00:53:40.360 --> 00:53:43.910
which has an established
religion, even churches have

00:53:43.910 --> 00:53:48.690
to prove that they're charitable
to receive government.

00:53:48.690 --> 00:53:52.140
Even the church of England
has to prove every year

00:53:52.140 --> 00:53:55.610
that it engages in
significant charitable activity.

00:53:55.610 --> 00:53:58.480
You don't just get it
because you're religious.

00:53:58.480 --> 00:54:01.260
&gt;&gt; Germany, France,
that kind of place?

00:54:01.260 --> 00:54:05.760
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sarah Barringer Gordon:
As far as I know, Germany,

00:54:05.760 --> 00:54:10.150
you can -- there's a box
you can check on your taxes

00:54:10.150 --> 00:54:13.640
that will allow a certain
proportion of them to go

00:54:13.640 --> 00:54:15.280
to religious organizations.

00:54:15.280 --> 00:54:19.520
And I think you can specify
a little bit, you know,

00:54:19.520 --> 00:54:22.480
you can't just say, "Send it
to the Jehovah's Witnesses

00:54:22.480 --> 00:54:26.900
down the street and definitely
not those creeps across the way,

00:54:26.900 --> 00:54:28.590
because they're not
really Jehovah's Witness."

00:54:28.590 --> 00:54:31.630
You know what I mean.

00:54:31.630 --> 00:54:38.800
In terms of tax exemption, being
the, really the only country

00:54:38.800 --> 00:54:46.260
with a stable disestablished
column, at least,

00:54:46.260 --> 00:54:49.260
the United States was
kind of on it's own,

00:54:49.260 --> 00:54:54.300
which is really,
really remarkable.

00:54:54.300 --> 00:54:55.620
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Any
other quick questions?

00:54:55.620 --> 00:54:57.810
Luke has one over here.

00:54:57.810 --> 00:54:59.110
Last question.

00:54:59.110 --> 00:55:01.330
&gt;&gt; Okay. Sally, I was
interested in the fact

00:55:01.330 --> 00:55:03.920
that you mentioned
Massachusetts was the first

00:55:03.920 --> 00:55:06.140
to pass tax exemption,
and they're the last

00:55:06.140 --> 00:55:08.580
to disestablish the
church, right?

00:55:08.580 --> 00:55:09.880
So they're the state

00:55:09.880 --> 00:55:13.230
where there's still
tax dollars, you know.

00:55:13.230 --> 00:55:14.540
They're actually supporting,

00:55:14.540 --> 00:55:17.130
I guess the congressional
church up until 1833.

00:55:17.130 --> 00:55:18.830
Is there a link between
Massachusetts,

00:55:18.830 --> 00:55:21.570
I mean is that sort of the
backlash to disestablishment

00:55:21.570 --> 00:55:23.480
that they get tax
exemptions at least.

00:55:23.480 --> 00:55:24.780
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sarah Barringer
Gordon: There are a couple

00:55:24.780 --> 00:55:27.110
of backlashes, I think
that's a great question.

00:55:27.110 --> 00:55:31.830
The other thing, so in 1837,
they passed tax exemption.

00:55:31.830 --> 00:55:39.650
In 1835, they prosecuted
a man for blasphemy

00:55:39.650 --> 00:55:41.220
and sent him too jail, right?

00:55:41.220 --> 00:55:44.450
So mean, there's
this remarkable --

00:55:44.450 --> 00:55:46.680
one of the things
see for example,

00:55:46.680 --> 00:55:49.750
when a government takes
a really big step,

00:55:49.750 --> 00:55:52.100
they often walk it
back, you know.

00:55:52.100 --> 00:55:54.570
Say, "It's not going to be
that radical of change people,

00:55:54.570 --> 00:55:57.360
don't worry too much."

00:55:57.360 --> 00:56:00.780
And so yes, I think

00:56:00.780 --> 00:56:05.260
that Massachusetts only
reluctantly disestablished

00:56:05.260 --> 00:56:13.160
and they did so truly because, I
mean, they were so duplicities,

00:56:13.160 --> 00:56:15.660
you know, before the revolution
they kept saying to the church

00:56:15.660 --> 00:56:20.100
of England, we have a beautiful
established church here,

00:56:20.100 --> 00:56:21.980
it's according to the
congregational form

00:56:21.980 --> 00:56:24.210
of the Church of England,
but it's beautiful.

00:56:24.210 --> 00:56:26.780
And then right after the
revolution they said,

00:56:26.780 --> 00:56:28.080
"Establishment?

00:56:28.080 --> 00:56:29.480
We have no establishment.

00:56:29.480 --> 00:56:32.210
We just have a policy
of supporting a teacher

00:56:32.210 --> 00:56:34.120
of religion in each town."

00:56:34.120 --> 00:56:37.000
Right. So I mean it really,
they caught themselves,

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:39.810
they were hoist on
their own petard.

